'''Robert Muller''' (March 11, 1923 – September 20, 2010) was an international [[Civil service|civil servant]] with the [[United Nations]]. Serving with the UN for 40 years and rising to the rank of [[Under-Secretary-General of the United Nations|Assistant Secretary-General]], his ideas about [[world government]], [[world peace]] and [[spirituality]] led to the increased representation of religions in the UN, especially of [[New Age Movement]]. He was known by some as "the philosopher of the United Nations".<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=964sAAAAIBAJ&sjid=wRQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2740%2C841277 "Schweitzer - Robert Muller"]. ''Star-News''. March 17, 1993.</ref>

==Early life and education==
Born in Belgium, Robert Muller grew up in the [[Alsace-Lorraine]] region in France as a French citizen.<ref name=autogenerated4>[http://www.douglasgillies.com/prophet.html Prophet - the Hatmaker's Son. The life of Robert Muller<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Alsace-Lorraine borders Germany. His childhood home was on the border. The border issues he saw as a child had a significant impact on his life, his decision to work at the United Nations. During his youth Robert Muller experienced constant political and cultural turmoil. He knew the horrors of [[World War II]], of being a refugee, of the [[Nazi]] occupation in France, imprisonment and escape from prison. During the war he was a member of the [[French Resistance]] where towards the end of the war he unsuccessfully tried to prevent the slaughter of a group of captured German soldiers. This was a major life event that led to work for [[peace]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120629101649/http://odewire.com/60542/the-happiest-man-on-earth.html "The happiest man on earth"].''Ode Magazine''. January 21, 2007.</ref><ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=zE9OAAAAIBAJ&sjid=4_gDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5855,1807329&dq=dr-robert-muller&hl=en "U.N. Official Says Life Should Be 1st Alliance"]. ''Spokane Daily Chronicle''. October 25, 1976.</ref> After the war he returned home and earned a Doctorate of Law from the [[University of Strasbourg]]. In 1948 he entered and won an essay contest on how to govern the world, the prize of which was an internship at the newly created United Nations.<ref name=autogenerated4 />

==Career==
Dr. Muller began working at the United Nations just as it was forming. He devoted the next 40 years of his life behind the scenes at the United Nations, focusing his energies on nurturing a better world, including working for the environment, economics and peace. He was instrumental in the conception of many multilateral bodies, including the [[UN Development Programme]], the [[World Food Programme]], the [[UN Population Fund]], and the [[World Youth Assembly]].<ref>[https://www.un.org/sg/statements/?nid=5132 United Nations Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon's Statements<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He rose through the ranks at the UN to the official position of Assistant Secretary-General and served under three [[UNSG|Secretaries-General]].

Robert Muller created a "World Core [[Curriculum]]"<ref>[http://www.unol.org/rms/wcc.html "World Core Curriculum"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120606090937/http://www.unol.org/rms/wcc.html |date=2012-06-06 }}</ref> that earned him the [[UNESCO Prize for Peace Education]] in 1989.<ref name=autogenerated1>[[UNESCO Prize for Peace Education]]</ref> The "World Core Curriculum" helped inspire the growing Global Education movement. More than 30 Robert Muller schools were founded throughout the world, including LIFE School in [[Panajachel]], Guatemala, from which students have gone on to pursue degrees in International Affairs.

He was the recipient of multiple awards and honors, including the [[Albert Schweitzer International Prize for the Humanities]]<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=964sAAAAIBAJ&sjid=wRQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3069,637510&dq=dr-robert-muller&hl=en "3 to be honored for contributions to music, medicine, hymanities"] ''Star-News''. March 17, 1993</ref><ref name=autogenerated2>http://randall3.uncw.edu/ascod/createpdfsc.php?id=269</ref> and the [[Eleanor Roosevelt Man of Vision Award]].

In addition to his duties at the [[University for Peace]], he devoted time to his writings and was an internationally acclaimed, multilingual speaker<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=BRBJAAAAIBAJ&sjid=jgUNAAAAIBAJ&pg=1831,4247439&dq=dr-robert-muller&hl=en "Peace topic of Darien talk"] ''The hour''. November 25, 1985</ref><ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=FSFOAAAAIBAJ&sjid=mu0DAAAAIBAJ&pg=2231,5320229&dq=dr-robert-muller&hl=en "Plans start for U.N. Day"] ''The Spokesman-Review''. September 15, 1976</ref> and author of fourteen books published in various languages.<ref name=autogenerated3>[http://www.upeace.org/news/activity.cfm?id_activity=653&actual=2010 The University for Peace - Admissions<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> One of his major writings came from writing one idea-dream each day for nurturing a better world. His goal was to have written 2000 ideas and dreams by the beginning of the new millennium. He achieved this and went on to write over 7000 ideas and dreams. In his speeches he spoke of these idea-dreams and over the years noted that many of these ideas were being worked on and some had been completed.

At the prompting of many of his friends, admirers and non-governmental organizations, Robert Muller was a candidate as a global citizen in 1996 for the post of [[Secretary-General of the United Nations]].<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=fXpaAAAAIBAJ&sjid=rR4EAAAAIBAJ&pg=3797,5148568&dq=dr+robert+muller&hl=en "Irish woman may yet replace Boutros-Ghali"] ''New Straits Times''. May 30, 1996</ref> He was also nominated multiple times for the [[Nobel Peace Prize]].{{fact|date=April 2018}}

Robert Muller died on September 20, 2010.

==Honors and awards==
* UNESCO Prize for Peace Education<ref name=autogenerated1 /> in 1989
* Albert Schweitzer International Prize for the Humanities<ref name=autogenerated2 /> in 1993
* Eleanor Roosevelt Man of Vision Award in 1994
* Muller was also a member of the Advisory Council of the [[Nuclear Age Peace Foundation]], and received the Foundation's World Citizenship Award in 2002.<ref>[http://www.wagingpeace.org/menu/programs/awards-&-contests/wca-award/ World Citizenship Award] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120307115938/http://www.wagingpeace.org/menu/programs/awards-%26-contests/wca-award/ |date=2012-03-07 }}, Nuclear Age Peace Foundation</ref>
* Goi Peace Award 2003<ref>[http://www.goipeace.or.jp/english/activities/award/award2003.html "GOI Peace Award 2003: Dr. Robert Muller"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090817025253/http://www.goipeace.or.jp/english/activities/award/award2003.html |date=2009-08-17 }}, GOI Peace Foundation</ref>
* Honored by the New York Open Center<ref>[http://www.opencenter.org/galahonorees/ Retrieved 2010-08-12.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091103190743/http://www.opencenter.org/galahonorees/ |date=2009-11-03 }}</ref> in 2005 for his "Lifetime Dedication to World Peace and Global Education".

